text: Progress in Total Syntheses of Anti-malignant Pleural Mesothelioma Compounds Key Laboratory of Green Chemistry & Technology of the Ministry of Education, College of Chemistry, Sichuan University, Chengdu 610064, China (Received: October 13, 2017; Accepted: December 28, 2017; DOI: 10.1002/jccs.201700360) Malignant pleural mesothelioma (MPM) is a rare malignant tumor occurring in the mesothelial cell of the pleural cavity. It would grow over the serosal sur- face and ﬁnally encase the lung, leading to death by asphyxiation. According to pathological studies, MPM is associated with exposure to asbestos ﬁbers, viral *Corresponding author. Email: chembliu@scu.edu.cn Malignant pleural mesothelioma (MPM) is a fatal tumor, which spreads aggressively and highly resists conventional chemotherapeutic agents. It continues to be a difﬁcult clinical problem, and efﬁcient treatment is still an enormous challenge. Alimta is used currently as an anti-MPM medi- cine, obtained mainly through chemical syntheses. Meanwhile, phenanthroindolizidine alkaloids such as tylophorine and cuevaene A, diterpenes such as cafestol and kahweol, naphthoquinones such as JBIR-76 and JBIR-77, anagucycline C-glycosides, and dodecahydrodibenzo[b,d]furan skel- etons such as JBIR-23 and JBIR-24 have been isolated and found with different cytotoxic effects against several MPM cell lines. The present short review summarizes the synthetic strategies of these anti-MPM molecules. Keywords: Malignant pleural mesothelioma; Cytotoxic; Synthesis. Yi Man was born in Sichuan, China, in 1993. She received the B.Sc. degree in chemistry from Sichuan Uni- versity (SU) in 2015. She is now pursuing the PhD degree at SU in Prof. Bo Liu’s group. She is currently working on the total synthesis of complex natural products.

Bo Liu was born in Chongqing, China, in 1976. He obtained the B.Sc. degree in environmental chemistry from Southwest Normal University (currently Southwest University) in 1998. He then began his research career under the supervision of Prof. Xiaoming Feng at Chengdu Institute of Organic Chemistry (CIOC, CAS). After he obtained the M.Sc. degree in 2001, he joined Prof. Wei-Shan Zhou’s group at the Shanghai Institute of Organic Chemistry (SIOC, CAS) to work on the total syntheses of steroids and polyketides. He obtained the PhD degree in 2004. After Postdoctoral research from 2004 to 2007, supervised by Prof. Jef K. De Brabander at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, USA, he joined the Col- lege of Chemistry, Sichuan University, as a faculty member. In 2014, he received the Thieme Chemistry Journal Award. His current research interests are focused on the total syntheses of natural products, synthesis-oriented methodology, and medicine synthesis. © 2018 The Chemical Society Located in Taipei & Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. MPM is resis- tant to all conventional therapies, including chemother- apy, radiotherapy, and surgery, and the prognosis of patients remains very poor.1–3 Alimta with platinum complexes is the only treatment, but it is the front-line JOURNAL OF THE CHINESE CHEMICAL SOCIETY

standard of care, whereas there are no approved second-line treatment for MPM. Clinical Phase III studies have shown that the remission rate of MPM is 41.3% through these treatments, the median time to progression is 5.7 months, and median overall survival is 12.1 months.4 These times have increased signiﬁ- cantly compared to contrasting groups, but the mean survival time is only 18 months. It is imperative that novel therapeutic agents against MPM and new treat- ments should be urgently developed. After decades of development, scientists have isolated a number of new molecules that show anti-MPM activity (Figure 1). This article summarizes the syntheses of these anti- MPM compounds. Fig. 1. KGaA, Weinheim TOTAL SYNTHESES OF ANTI-MPM MOLECULES Total syntheses of Alimta Alimta (Pemetrexed) is the only anti-MPM drug available on the market, developed by Taylor and coworkers at Princeton University in 1992.5 It belongs to the class of antifolic agents but is distinguished from the other antifolic compounds, with a unique 6/5 fused pyrrolo-[2,3-d]pyrimidine instead of the classical pteri- dine or quinazline structure as in methotrexate or raltitrexed. Taylor and coworkers synthesized the 5,10- dideaze-5,6,7,8-trtrahydrofolic acid 13 (DDATHF), which is an active antitumor compound (Figure 2).6 To examine the contribution of its C-6 stereogenic center to the bioactivity, they synthesized the pyrrolopyrimi- dine DDATHF analog 1 (Alimta) (Scheme 1). Surpris- ingly, Alimta showed excellent inhibitory activity to tumor growth in vitro and in vivo. Fig. 2. Structure of 5,10-dideaze-5,6,7,8-trtrahydrofolic Scheme 1. Total synthesis of Alimta by Taylor et al.

Progress in Total Syntheses of Anti-MPM Compounds The synthesis started with 7-deazaguanine.7 How- ever, treatment of compound 14 with bromine could not give the desired brominated products. Oxidation of 14 led to the failure in this process. Then, the free amino was protected, generating the 2-pivalogy deriva- tive 15. Attempt to brominate 15 also failed. But iodin- ation of 15 using the N-iodosuccinimide in DMF yielded the 7,8-diiodo derivative 16. And the 7-iodo intermediate 17 was regioselectively accessed from com- pound 16 with zinc and acetic acid.8 The complete framework of the target product was constructed via a palladium-catalyzed coupling between 17 and 20.9 The triple bond in compound 18 was selectively hydroge- nated without any deleterious inﬂuence of the pyrrole. The target compound was generated through treatment with 1 N sodium hydroxide, resulting in the hydrolysis of the methyl ester and removal of the pivaloyl protect- ing group. This route gave Alimta in 22% yield over six steps. In the following years, several different synthetic strategies for pyrrolo[2,3-d]pyrimidine were reported, which mainly relied on the palladium-catalyzed coupling to construct the framework.10 Taylor and coworkers uti- lized the novel manganic triacetate-induced cyclization to synthesize Alimta in 2001 (Scheme 2).10e Under the Mn(III)-catalyzed condition, cyclization of a variety of N-substituted malonamides 21, followed by guanidine annulation of 2-amino-4-pyrimidinone ring, afforded 3- carbomethoxy-2-pyrrolidinones 24. Then compound Scheme 2. Synthesis of Alimta in 2001. © 2018 The Chemical Society Located in Taipei & Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

26 was expected to be achieved via the Heck reaction. Surprisingly, compound 25 was formed instead, via palladium-catalyzed coupling with diethyl 4-iodoben- zoyglutamate. It indicated that the palladium adduct formed the intermediate C (Scheme 3). First, oxidative addition iodobenzoylglutamate with palladium catalysis afforded A. Then coordination of the Heck-type product with the palladium–hydrogen complex, followed by migration insertion, gave the intermediate B, which led to the complex C. Pyrrolopyrimidine 25 was generated through repetition of the above process. Alimta was converted from compound 25 via removal of the N-protecting group and hydrolysis of the ester. Subsequently, Taylor and coworkers reported in 2003 a new synthetic strategy toward Alimta, which involved Michael addition, Nef reaction, and intramo- lecular cyclization (Scheme 4).11 Henry reaction between commercially available hydrocinnamaldehyde 3310b with nitromethane, followed by dehydration, yielded the ester 34. Compound 35 was easily prepared after Michael addition of 34, in excellent yield. A new strat- egy for the generation the 5/6 bicyclic ring system of pyrrolo[2,3-d]pyrimidine was developed (Scheme 5). First, the precursor 29 was achieved from the Michael adduct of 28. Then, Nef reaction afforded the amino aldehyde 31, which gave the pyrrole ring via intramolec- ular condensation. Following this condition, 36 was gen- erated from compound 35 in 57% yield by means of a one-pot, three-step process. Based on the above synthetic routes, scientists improved the synthesis procedure reported in patents, in order to facilitate mass industrial production of Alimta. Total syntheses of cafestol and kahweol In 1959, cafestol (2) was ﬁrst isolated from coffee drinks,12 and its natural analog kahweol (3) was iso- lated in 1963.13 They are diterpenoids featuring a bicyclo[3,2,1]-octane motif decorated with a furan ring. Shim and coworkers showed that the estimated IC50 values of cafestol and kahweol were 82.07 and 56.00 μM in MSTO-211H, respectively. Cafestol and kahweol could regulate the speciﬁcity protein 1 (Sp1) target proteins, resulting in apoptosis by suppression of SP1 levels in MSTO-211H cells, which could be used as therapeutic target in cancer research.14 Scheme 4. Corey and coworkers reported the ﬁrst synthesis of ((cid:1))-cafestol in 1987 (Scheme 6).15 Compound 39 was formed from the bicyclic ketone 38 via methylation. The iodide 40 was prepared from 39 in ﬁve steps.16 Treatment of the iodide 35 with deprotonated methyl cyclohexa-1, 3-diene-5-carboxylate gave the tricyclic ester 41 in 67% yield.17 The diazoketone 42 was gener- ated from compound 41 in two steps. With the slow addition of copper(II) bissalicylaldehyde-tert-butylimi- nein, the diazoketone 42 selectively formed the ester 43 via cyclopropanation in 45% yield.18 Treatment of compound 43 with sodium borohydride in methanol afforded the alcohol 44. After protection of compound 44, reduction of the ester using DIBAL-H afforded 45.19 With triﬂic anhydride and 2,6-lutidine, compound 46 was formed via cationic cyclization of the alcohol 45. The diene 47 was formed via routine functional group operation in ﬁve steps. Then the furan ring was protected by the bulky TIPS group to avoid oxidation. The target molecule was generated from 48 via selective hydroxylation of the exocyclic bond, hydrogenation of the endocyclic double bond, and removal of the protec- tion in 0.5% overall yield in 23 steps. In 2014, Hong and coworkers reported an efﬁcient approach to the total synthesis of ((cid:1))-cafestol via a bioinspried strategy (Scheme 8).21 Biosynthesis of cafestol is supposed to start with geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGDP), though polyene cyclization to form ent-kaurene (Scheme 9). After methyl migration from C-17 to C-18, furan is formed, and the dihydroxylation of alkene takes place to com- plete synthesis of cafestol. The synthetic strategy by Hong’s group followed the pipeline of cafestol biosyn- thesis (Scheme 10). Polycyclization and Claisen rearran- gement of the polyene compound would construct the bicycle [3, 2, 1]octane motif, thus ﬁnishing the quater- nary carbon center of C-8. The furan ring could be gen- erated at a later stage.

Accordingly, Suzuki coupling of 3-methoxystyrene 54 with vinyliodide 53 gave the alcohol 55.22 Treatment of 55 with IBX gave the enal 56 in 94% yield. But treat- ment of compound 56 with SnCl4 gave low yield and selectivity. If an aluminum complex was used, the stereoselectivity of an aldehyde–ene cyclization showed a preference for a chair-like conformation under Snider and Brown’s model (Scheme 11). JOURNAL OF THE CHINESE CHEMICAL SOCIETY promoted this carbonyl–ene cyclization with 75% yield and cis selectivity.23 When the reaction temperature was quickly increased to room temperature, the ratio of trans/cis isomers increased, which indicated that the trans product was generated though a thermodynami- cally favored boat-like conformation.

After compound cis-57 was obtained in 75% yield, Birch reduction with hydrochloric acid work-up afforded the enone 58. The subsequent Lüche reduction afforded the allylic alcohol 59. The Eschenmoser–Claisen rearran- gement established the quaternary carbon center of C-8 in 60.24 Compound 61 was obtained from 60 through lac- tonization, elimination, and protection. Reduction of the lactone 61 using DIBAL-H and SmI2-mediated cycliza- tion gave the desired the diol 62 in 90% yield.25 The sec- ondary alcohol at C-16 was selectively oxidized by DMP. The desired bicyclo[3, 2, 1]octane was formed via Wittig oleﬁnation and Barton–McCombie radical deoxygen- ation in 64% yield in three steps.26 Deprotection of com- pound 64, followed by DMP oxidation, furnished the ketone 65. Treatment of compound 65 with Vedejs’ reagent (MoOPH) gave the hydroxylation product 66 as a single diastereomer in 89% yield.27 Nucleophilic addi- tion using ethynylmagnesium bromide in THF afforded the major stereoisomer. Treatment of 67 with a gold cata- lyst gave the furan 68 in excellent yield.28 The subsequent dihydroxylation using stoichiometric osmium tetroxide completed total synthesis of cafestol. Hong’s route com- pleted the total synthesis of this natural product in 5% yield over 22 steps. 11. Gräfe and coworkers isolated a natural triene cue- vaene A product from Streptomyces sp. HKI 0180 (Fig. 3).29 In 2013, Shin-ya and coworkers also derived cuevaene A from the Streptomyces sp. 30503. In 2009, JBIR-23 (6) and JBIR-24 (7) were isolated from the same species by Shin-ya and coworkers.30 These three 4-methoxy-6- natural methylheptatrienoic acid side chain and may be synthe- sized via similar biosynthetic pathways. Thus Shin-ya and coworkers suspected that the structure of cuevaene A proposed by Gräfe’s group might be incorrect and suggested another structure. Cuevaene A, JBIR-23, and JBIR-24 are effective against various MPM cell lines. Cuevaene A exhibited cytotoxic activities against Meso- 1, Meso-8A, and Meso-8D with IC50 values of 32, 40, 78 μM, respectively.31 The total

synthesis of cuevaene A was ﬁrst reported by Liu and coworkers in 2010 (Scheme 12).32 With commercially available 2-cyclohexen-1-one as the starting molecule, Michael addition using the vinyl Gri- gnard reagent in the presence of Cu(I) quenched TMSCl, and afforded the sily ether 71.33 The following boron triﬂuoride-promoted Mukaiyama aldol cycliza- tion of compound 71 with p-benzoquinone gave the benzofuran 72.34 Protection of free phenol gave the TBS silyl ether 73, and Johnson–Lemieux oxidation and subsequent Wittig reaction afforded the ester 74. The second trisubstituted alkene fragment was con- structed via reduction, oxidation, and WHE reaction sequentially. The third disubstituted alkene was formed from the ester 75 similarly via sequential reduction, oxi- dation, and Wittig reaction. Treatment of compound 76 with lithium hydroxide completed the total synthesis of cuevaene A by removing the TBS group and hydro- lyzing the ester simultaneously. This strategy achieved cuevaene A in overall 5% yield over 13 steps. Fig. 3. Proposed structures of cuevaene A. Progress in Total Syntheses of Anti-MPM Compounds

In 2012, Taylor and coworkers synthesized cue- vaene A from 4-methoxyphenol (Scheme 13).35 Follow- ing a known procedure, the monoketal 78 was prepared by the oxidative dearomatization of 4-methoxyphe- nol.36 tBuOK-promoted double Michael addition of compound 78 produced the intermediate 79, which was followed by an acid-catalyzed rearrangement to afford exclusively the ketone 80.37 Compound 80 was trans- formed to the phenol 81 via Peterson oleﬁnation. After protection of the free phenol of compound 81, the alco- hol 83 was achieved via Brown hydroboration. Swern oxidation of compound 83 gave the aldehyde 84 in 72% yield. Based on the strategy developed by Liu’s group,32 the 4-methoxy-6-methyl-heptatrienoic acid side chain was constructed in seven steps. Here, the TBS protec- tive group of compound 82 could be retained by using only 1 equiv of KHMDS in the generation of com- pound 88. The over yield of cuevaene A was 7% over 14 steps. Total syntheses of tylophorine Tylophorine, a phenanthoindolizidine alkaloid, was ﬁrst isolated in 1935 from the genera Cynanchum, Pergularia, and Tylophora.38 It exhibits a variety of bio- logical properties, including antitumor, anti-amoebic, and antifungal activities. In cytotoxicity against human MPM ACC-Meso-1 cells, tylophorine showed an IC50 Scheme 12. value of 3.1 μM.39 Because of its potent biological activities and interesting structure, several synthetic strategies have been reported. The ﬁrst racemic total synthesis of tylophorine reported in 196140 was linear with only ﬁve steps starting with a known 2,3,6,7-tetra- methoxy-9-chloromethylphena-nthrene 91 (Scheme 14). Treatment of pyrrylmagnesium bromide with the known compound 91, followed by reduction using hydrogen in acetic acid with Adams catalysis, generated the pyrrolidine 93. Cyclization of the N-formyl deriva- tive 94 gave the salt 95, which was converted to the nat- ural product via reduction using sodium borohydride. Wang and coworkers developed an asymmetric synthesis of (S)-tylophorine from azido aldehyde in 2013 via a one-pot intramolecular Schmidt, Bischler– Napierlski reaction and an imine-reduction sequence (Scheme 15).41 The enantioselective strategy began with the amidation of azido acid 97 and commercially avail- able 96, leading to the N-acylated oxazolidine 98. The single diastereomer 101 was generated from the phenan- thryl bromide 100 through the stereoselective alkylation JOURNAL OF THE CHINESE CHEMICAL SOCIETY with compound 98. Reduction using DIBAL-H afforded the aldehyde 102 via removal of the auxiliary. Triﬂuoroacetic acid was found in regioselectivity and stereochemistry of the intramolecular Schmidt rearran- gement. After optimization of conditions, compound 103 was transformed into the intermediate 104 with using triﬂuoroacetic anhydride through Bischer-Napier- alski reaction. Subsequent treatment with sodium boro- hydride ﬁnished synthesis of the natural product. The novel enantioselective route was completed in 48% overall yield over ﬁve steps. Scheme 15. KGaA, Weinheim One year later, a novel strategy toward the synthe- sis of (S)-tylophorine was reported by Wang’s group via one-pot Curtius rearrangement and Friedel–Crafts reaction (Scheme 16).42 Under Evans’s stereoselective alkylation conditions, coupling oxazolidinone 106 and phenanthryl bromide 105 gave compound 107 as a sin- gle diastereomer.43 Hydrolysis of the chiral auxiliary was undertaken with lithium hydroxide and hydrogen peroxide to afford 108. Treatment of the acid 108 with diphenylphosphoryl azide (DPPA) and triethylamine in situ generated the isocyanate 109 via Curtius rearrange- ment. Under Lewis acid BF3(cid:3)OEt2 catalysis, the lactam 110 was obtained via intramolecular Friedel–Crafts (S)- cyclization. Asymmetric tylophorine was then accomplished in four linear steps. In 2016, Opatz and coworkers reported the total synthesis of phenanthroindolizidine alkaloids including (S)-tylophorine, via a free-radical cyclization in 49% overall yield over ﬁve linear steps (Scheme 17).44 2,3- Diphenylacylic acid 113 was prepared via condensation of commercially available veratraldehyde 112 and homoveratric acid 111. Oxidative cyclization of the acid 113 using sodium nitrite and air in an acid medium afforded phenanthrene-9-carboxylic acid 114.45 Subse- quent amidation afforded 115. The radical precursor 116 could be accomplished from compound 115 via iodoamino-cyclization.46 Then direct ring formation through C–H alkylation, mediated by Pd(PPh3)4 and K2CO3, afforded the desired pentacyclic lactam 117 in Scheme 16. Other novel anti-MPM compounds, namely JBIR- 23(6) and JBIR-24 (7), were reported by Shin-ya and coworkers, which were isolated from Streptomyces sp. - AK-AB27 in 2011.30 JBIR-23 inhibited the growth of the MPM cells lines including MESO-1, MSTO-211H, NCI-H290, and NCI-H2052, with IC50 values of 25, 50, 10, 20 μM, respectively, in a dose- and time- dependent manner (Table 1). The cytotoxic activity of JBIR-23 was eightfold higher than that of JBIR-24, which exhibited cytotoxic activities against these MPM cells with IC50 values of 190, >200, 75, and 150 μM, respectively. This review has summarized the syntheses of a number of compounds exhibiting signiﬁcant antitumor efﬁcacy in MPM cells, which are expected to be invalu- able lead compounds for anti-MPM drugs. Predictably, as efﬁcient synthetic strategies and new methodologies are developed, total synthesis of anti-MPM compounds and other biologically active complex compounds will be achieved in satisfactory overall yield and selectivity.
